THESIS
In this thesis, we solve some disadvantages of deep neural networks with Bayesian
approach. Specically, we proposed a novel and effective structured approxi-
mate inference framework for deep Bayesian nets, named Variational Structured
Dropout (VSD). The main contributions are as follows:
1. Our structured approximation is implemented on low dimensional Dropout
noise with considerable computational efciency, instead of performing com-
plex and expensive techniques directly on the random weights as the previous
works. By low-rank approximation, we can greatly reduce the number of pa-
rameters compared to the mean-eld BNNs.
2. VSD is a general learning method that can be applied to different network ar-
chitectures. Especially, VSD can be employed for modern deep convolutional
networks in a direct way while maintaining the backpropagation in parallel
and optimizing efciently with stochastic gradient methods.
3. To make our approximation more expressive, we exploit a hierarchical Dropout
procedure, which is equivalent to infer a joint posterior in a hierarchical Bayesian
nets. This posterior can be approximated as a mixture of structured covariance
Gaussian, which has a reasonable potential to recover the multimodality of the
true Bayesian posterior.
4. We carry out extensive experiments with many standard datasets and differ-
ent network architectures. Empirical results have evidenced the advantages
of VSD such as well-calibrated prediction, better generalization, good uncer-
tainty estimation, robustness to out-of-distribution settings.

Abstract
Bayesian methods promise to address many shortcomings of deep learning. How-
ever, core learning algorithms of deep Bayesian models usually employ approxi-
mate inference frameworks, which exhibits a dilemma of how to yield high delity
posterior approximations while maintaining computational efciency and scalabil-
ity. We tackle this challenge by introducing a new variational structured approxi-
mation inspired by the interpretation of Dropout training as approximate inference
in Bayesian probabilistic models. Concretely, we focus on restrictions of the fac-
torized structure of Dropout posterior which is inexible to capture rich correla-
tions among weight parameters of the true posterior, and we then propose a novel
method called Variational Structured Dropout (VSD) to overcome this limitation.
VSD employs an orthogonal transformation to learn a structured representation on
the variational Dropout noise and consequently induces statistical dependencies
in the approximate posterior. We further gain an expressive Bayesian modeling
for VSD via proposing a hierarchical Dropout procedure that corresponds to the
joint inference in a Bayesian network. Moreover, we can scale up VSD to modern
deep convolutional networks in a direct way with low computational cost. Finally,
we conduct extensive experiments on standard benchmarks to demonstrate the ef-
fectiveness of VSD over state-of-the-art methods on both predictive accuracy and
uncertainty estimation.
This work is in the line of research of the following papers:

3. Van-Son Nguyen, Duc-Tung Nguyen, Linh Ngo Van, Khoat Than, Innite

CHAPTER 1. INRODUCTION
1.1 The problem
Deep learning has become a revolution with many tremendous successes impacting
comprehensively almost all elds of both scientic research and applied industry.
Although it has signicantly advanced the state of the art in terms of predictive
accuracy of various tasks, deep neural networks still suffer from some critical lim-
itations. They require a large amount of high-quality data for effective training
but are also more prone to overtting in the regime of small data. This limits the
application of the deep network model to essential problems of scarce data such as
medical images and security. Furthermore, deep neural nets trained with point esti-
mate procedures tend to be overcondent leading to uncalibrated prediction in the
out-of-distribution setting. More importantly, they also lack principles to provide
the condence interval in prediction as well as estimate the model uncertainty. This
is extremely crucial in reliable decision-based systems such as robotics, medical
diagnosis, autonomous driving, etc.
Figure 1.1: Predictive distribution of LeNet5 architecture for a continuously rotated ver-
sion of a 3 from MNIST. Each colour corresponds to a different class and the height of the
bar denotes the probability assigned to that particular class by the network. Left: deter-
ministic training. Right: Bayesian neural nets
Bayesian neural networks (BNNs) [1][3] have been promoted to address the prob-
lems aforementioned. Bayesian principle for deep learning models offers a prob-
abilistic interpretation for deep learning models by imposing a prior distribution
on the weight parameters and aim to obtain a posterior distribution instead of only
point estimates. By marginalizing over this posterior for prediction, BNNs per-
form a procedure of ensemble learning. These principles facilitate the model to
improve generalization, robustness and allow for uncertainty quantication. A sim-
ple example can be seen at Figure 1.1. The predictive distribution of deterministic
1
training becomes overly overcondent, namely assigns a high softmax probability,
towards the wrong class for things it has not seen before (e.g. an MNIST 3 rotated
by 90 degrees). On the other hand, the condence of the network for the unseen
digits is drastically reduced when we are using a Bayesian model, thus resulting in
more realistic predictive distributions.
However, due to the high dimensionality of model parameters and the non-linearity
of activation functions, computing exactly the posterior of deep Bayesian networks
is infeasible and approximate inference has been devised. The core challenge is
how to construct an expressive approximation for the true posterior while maintain-
ing computational efciency and scalability, especially for modern deep learning
architectures.
1.2 Related works
Laplace approximation is one of the rst attempts to solve the above approximate
inference problem in which the approximate posterior is tted by a Gaussian dis-
tribution centered at MAP estimate of the weight parameters with the covariance
matrix determined by the inverse of the Hessian of log-likelihood [2]. However,
this method has some drawbacks such as the approximate posterior is unimodal
and the empirical approximation version of the Hessian matrix is either not com-
putationally efcient or not expressive enough in high dimensional space. An al-
ternative stochastic approximation for Bayesian neural nets based on the sampling
technique is called Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) [2]. This method does not
place any prior assumptions over the posterior structure, and able to capture com-
plicated multimodality of the true posterior and predictive distribution. Neverthe-
less, this method also has the disadvantage of being very expensive due to storing
many posterior samples across phases of the iterative schema. Furthermore, the
theoretical convergence is non-trivial to guarantee in practice.
Variational inference can overcome the limitations of the above approaches by
offering a deterministic approximation framework that casts the inference as an
optimization-based problem. This approach has been investigated from the early
stages of Bayesian neural nets by [3], [4] and achieved remarkable improvements
especially in recent researches. [5] rstly introduced a practical way to adapt varia-
tional inference to neural networks by employing data sub-sampling technique and
approximating the intractable expected log-likelihood with Monte Carlo estimate.
However, this method still showed poor performance in practice such as regression
task in [6]. [7] proposed Bayes by Backprop that utilized the reparameterization
2
trick [8][10] combined with the Monte Carlo sampling to derive an unbiased dif-
ferentiable estimation for variational objective and it then can be straightforwardly
optimized using standard stochastic gradient methods. Nonetheless, this approx-
imation usually exhibits a high variance of the gradient estimator in the context
of training deep Bayesian nets. [11] proposed the local reparameterization trick
that translates uncertainty about global random weights into local noise in pre-
activation unit and yields an alternative estimator whose variance is inversely pro-
portional to the minibatch size, generally leading to much stable training and faster
convergence.
Improving the variational approximation. The above works mainly focus on
factorized structure for approximate posterior, i.e mean-eld variational inference.
Generally, the mean-eld approximation family encourages some advantages in
inference including computational tractability and effective optimization with the
stochastic gradient-based methods. However, it will ignore strong statistical depen-
dencies among random weights of the neural networks, which leads to an inability
to capture the complicated structure of the true posterior and to estimate true model
uncertainty.
To tackle this drawback, many of extensive studies proposed to approximate the
true posterior with richer expressiveness. [12] proposed to treat the weight matrix
as a whole via a matrix variate Gaussian [13] and approximate the posterior based
on the parametrization of this distribution. By leveraging the local reparameter-
ization trick, they also provided a connection with deep Gaussian process. This
approximation is also made more scalable by incorporating with the probabilistic
backpropagation framework [6], [14]. Several later works have inherited and ex-
ploited this distribution to investigate different structured representations for the
variational Gaussian posterior, such as Kronecker-factored [15], [16], k-tied distri-
bution [17], non-centered or rank-1 parameterization [18], [19].
Another original idea to represent the true covariance matrix of variational Gaus-
sian posterior is to apply the low-rank approximation. This technique is exploited
in many different variants, based on Cholesky decomposition [20], sparse covari-
ance matrix [21], and low-rank plus diagonal structure [22][25]. For robust ap-
proximation with skewness, kurtosis, and multimodality, [26] proposed multiplica-
tive normalizing ow which adapts Hierarchical variational model framework [27]
for infering an implcit marginal distribution in high dimensional Bayesian set-
ting. However, the variational objective in their method requires computing an
intractable integral and leads to a further lower bound. Moreover, this method also
3
is expensive due to employing two sequences of normalizing ow to tighten the
approximation.
Although it has demonstrated good empirical performance, the structured Bayesian
method above still suffers a trade-off in computational complexity and scalability.
More notably, Matrix variate Gaussian and approximations based on low-rank are
not trivial to integrate into modern deep convolution networks. This is because it is
too expensive with a very high dimensional convolution layer and also challenging
to employ the reparameterization trick, so leads to a high variance in the gradient
estimator
1.3 The approach
Motivations. In this thesis, we approach the structured posterior approximation
in Bayesian neural networks from a different perspective which has been inspired
by the Bayesian interpretation of Dropout training [28], [29]. More specically,
the methods proposed in [11], [30] reinterpret Dropout regularization as approxi-
mation inference in deep Bayesian models and based on this connection to learn
a variational Dropout posterior over the weight parameters. From the literature,
we are promoted by the fact that inference approaches based on Bayesian Dropout
are often asymptotic or comparable in terms of predictive accuracy to the struc-
tured Bayesian methods aforementioned, but with much cheaper computational
complexity. Moreover, with impressive empirical results on various tasks along
with solid theories on effective regularization [31][33], generalization bound [34],
[35], convergence rate or robust optimization [36], [37], Dropout principle offers
several potentials to further improve approximate inference in deep Bayesian nets.
However, these Bayesian Dropout methods have also employed a simple struc-
ture of the mean-eld family, their approximation can suffer from some patholo-
gies such as underestimating the model uncertainty [38], ill-posed or singularity
inference [39]. We also clarify that our work has not been motivated primarily
for the purpose of improving dropout technique via the Bayesian perspective, but
more than that, we aim to exploit the relationship between dropout training and
Bayesian statistics to propose a more effective approximate inference framework
for deep Bayesian models.
Contributions. With the above insights, we propose a novel structured variational
inference framework based on Dropout principle. Our method adopts an orthog-
onal approximation called Householder transformation to learn a structured rep-
resentation for multiplicative Gaussian noise in Variational Dropout method [11],
4
[40], [41]. As a consequence of the Bayesian interpretation, we go beyond the
mean-eld family and obtain a variational Dropout posterior with structured co-
variance. Furthermore, to make our approximation more expressive, we exploit a
hierarchical Dropout procedure, which is equivalent to infer a joint posterior in a
hierarchical Bayesian nets. We name the proposed method as Variational Struc-
tured Dropout (VSD) and summarize its advantages as follows:
1. Our structured approximation is implemented on low dimensional Dropout
noise with considerable computational efciency, instead of performing complex
and expensive techniques directly on the random weights as the previous works.
By low-rank approximation, we can greatly reduce the number of parameters com-
pared to the mean-eld BNNs.
2. VSD is a general learning method that can be applied to different network
architectures. Especially, VSD can be employed for modern deep convolutional
networks in a direct way while maintaining the backpropagation in parallel and
optimizing efciently with stochastic gradient methods.
3. The variational posterior of VSD can be approximated as a mixture of structured
covariance Gaussian, which has a reasonable potential to recover the multimodality
of the true Bayesian posterior.
4. Finally, We carry out extensive experiments with many standard datasets and
different network architectures. Empirical results have evidenced the advantages
of VSD such as well-calibrated prediction, better generalization, good uncertainty
estimation, robustness to out-of-distribution settings.
1.4 Structure of the thesis
The rest of the thesis is organized as follows. We provide background for varia-
tional inference in Bayesian neural networks and describe the variational Bayesian
Dropout in Section 2. Then we present variational structured Dropout and provide
in-depth analyses of its expressiveness and scalability in Section 3. We empirically
show that our method improves both predictive accuracy and uncertainty measures
over existing methods in the experiments Section 4. We conclude the thesis in
Section 5 while deferring the additional materials in the Supplementary Material.

niques for deep neural networks.

Dropout as Bayesian approximation. Bayesian modelling provides a theoreti-
cal framework which is useful for analysing and extending the deep learning al-

Bayesian neural network with random weight matrix dened by W = diag(S),

The Kullback-Leibler condition and some drawbacks. Bayesian interpretation
of Dropout training is guaranteed through the KL condition, in which, optimizing
the variational lower bound w.r.t the model parameter is equivalent to training the
deterministic Dropout objective. Therefore, the term D

Bayesian modeling in terms of exibility of both the prior and variational poste-
rior distribution. Concretely, the Dropout posterior in Variational Dropout and MC
Dropout all has a simple structure of the mean-eld family such as fully-factorized
Gaussian or a mixture of delta peaks that are not expressive enough to resemble
the complicated correlation in the true posterior, leading to underestimating the
true model uncertainty. Moreover, the log-uniform prior distribution in Variational
Gaussian dropout is an improper-prior, which can lead to the singularity of the
variational objective and cause the inference of posterior to be ill-posed [39].

training. We apply variational structured Dropout for convolutional layer by learn-

CHAPTER 4. EXPERIMENTS
In this section, we provide experimental evaluations to show the effectiveness of
our proposed methods compared with the existing methods in terms of both pre-
dictability and scalability. We focus mainly on variational inference methods of
the following two directions: the rst one is via approximating the posterior di-
rectly on the random weights of Bayesian nets, including Bayes by Backprop
(BBB) [7], Variational Matrix Gaussian (VMG) [12], low-rank approximations
(SLANG, ELRG) [25], [60]; and the second one is the Bayesian Dropout meth-
ods with MC Dropout (MCD) [30], [61], Variational Dropout (VD) [11], Varia-
tional Bayesian Dropout (VBD) [41], [54] and our method-Variational Structured
Dropout (VSD). In addition, we evaluate the performance of point estimate frame-
work as MAP in most of our experiments. Details about data descriptions, network
architectures, hyper-parameter tuning are presented in Appendix 6.5.
4.1 Regression with UCI datasets
We start with implementing a standard experiment for Bayesian regression task on
UCI dataset [62] proposed in [6].

network with one hidden layer of 50 units and ReLU activation functions. We

4.2 Image classication
We now compare the predictive performance of the aforementioned methods for
classication tasks on three standard image datasets: MNIST [65], CIFAR10 [66],
and SVHN [67]. We evaluate the predictive probabilities using the metrics in-
cluding negative log-likelihood (NLL), error rate, and expected calibration error
(ECE) [68], [69], in which, the error rate represents explicitly for the predictive
accuracy, while NLL and ECE capture how well a model estimates the predictive
uncertainty. Further discussions and some insights of these metrics are provided in
detail in Appendix 6.4.
Experimental setup: With the MNIST dataset, 60,000 training points were split
into a training set of 50,000 and a validation set of 10,000. We then vectorized
the images and trained using two fully connected Bayesian neural networks with
the size of hidden layers of 400x2 and 750x3 respectively. For the remaining two
datasets CIFAR10 and SVHN, we used the same simple convolutional neural net-
work consisting of two convolutional layers with 32 and 64 kernels, followed by a
fully connected network with one hidden layer of size 128.
We trained the models with the default Adam optimizer using learning rate 0.001,
batchsize 100, and the number of epochs 100. At the test time, we used 10 Monte
Carlo samples for all methods. We also used the number of Householder transfor-
mations T {1, 2, 3} for our method on all three datasets. With Bayes by Backprop
(BBB), we did not employ the local reparameterization trick, instead we used two
MC samples during the training follow the code published by the authors. We
utilized the available results of the baselines in the same setting, including NLL
and error rate of ELRG on MNIST and CIFAR10 dataset, error rate of VMG and
SLANG on MNIST dataset.
Results: The synthesis results of this experiment are in Table 4.3. By a general
observation, VSDs outperform other methods in most settings. More specically,
VSD with hierarchical prior (VSD-H) consistently obtains the best results on all
three metrics. While the lowest error rate implies the highest predictive accuracy,
the gures on NLL and ECE represent well-calibrated predictions in our model.
On the other hand, for the remaining methods, especially MAP and BBB, the error
rates are worse by a large margin compared to VSD (respectively about 9% and

to avoid the poor local optima or singularity in approximation [11], [39], [40]. As a conse-
quence, this can reduce the ensemble diversity in the predictions of this method that leads
to underestimate the uncertainty of predictive distribution.

4.6 Low-rank approximation for VSD
We investigate a low-rank structure in the fully connected layer used to parameterize the
Householder vectors in our method. Instead of using one layer with full size K K, we
add a low dimensional hidden layer with ReLU activation. The size of this hidden layer
is r {2, 5, 10}. This idea is quite natural because it reduces signicantly the number
of parameters in our method while ensuring exible parametrization for the Householder
vectors thanks to the nonlinearity in hidden activation.

CHAPTER 5. CONCLUSION
We proposed a new approximate inference framework for deep Bayesian nets,
named Variational Structured Dropout (VSD). The novelty of VSD is that we learn
a structured approximate posterior via the Dropout principle. Instead of perform-
ing complex and expensive techniques directly on the random weights of deep
Bayesian models, we approximate structured representation for low-dimensional
noise on deterministic neural nets. VSD is successful in acquiring a exible infer-
ence while maintaining computational efciency and scalability for deep convolu-
tional models.
We have carried out extensive experiments on various tasks including Bayesian
regression, image classication, and uncertainty estimation. Empirical results on
many standard datasets and architecture have evidenced the advantages of VSD
such as well-calibrated prediction, better generalization, good uncertainty estima-
tion. Given a consistent performance of VSD as presented throughout the thesis,
an extension of that method to other problems, such as Bayesian active learning or
reinforcement learning, is of interest.

6.3 Computational complexity
We describe here in detail the computational costs of the different algorithms, in
which the computation is considered when performing a forward pass through
per layer of the network. We also discuss the memory usage while construct-
ing the dynamic computation graph. To ease the presentation, we briey recall
the abbreviations of methods from the main text, in particular: Bayes by Back-
prop (BBB) [7], Variational Matrix Gaussian (VMG) [12], low-rank approxima-
tions (SLANG, ELRG) [25], [60]; and the Bayesian Dropout methods including
MC Dropout (MCD) [30], [61], Variational Dropout (VD) [11], and Variational
Bayesian Dropout (VBD) [41], [54].
Assume the weight matrix of the layer is of size K L. First, MAP estimation
performs a matrix multiplication with time cost K L to forward each input x
i
of size K in data batch B. MAP estimation needs to store the output of these
calculations which gives a memory cost L|B|.
Next, BBB with naive reparameterization trick, in practice, needs to use s 2 sam-
pled weights of dimension K L to reduce the variance of gradient estimator. This
makes the computation hard to be performed in parallel, thus incurs multiple costs
of both time and memory with O(sKL|B|) and O(sKL + L|B|) respectively. On the
other hand, with the local reparameterization trick that translates uncertainty about
global random weights into local noise in pre-activation unit, BBB can gain an al-
ternative unbiased estimator with low variance while maintaining low complexity
via sampling only a local noise. However, it requires two forward passes to obtain
means and variances of the pre-activation.
33
For VMF, SLANG, and ELRG, the detailed analysis can be found on the original
papers, and note that SLANG is a method that fails to employ the local reparame-
terization trick, thereby leading to very high complexity on both time and memory.
VSD adopts the advantage of Dropout training (VD) via just sampling the low
dimension noise instead of whole random weights. An additional benet is that
VSD only requires one forward pass in parallel compared with two steps of the
local reparameterization trick. When using a fully connected layer (FC) size of
K K to parameterize the Householder vector, namely:

If the predicted probabilities are overcondent, NLL will severely penalize incor-

results on NLL. Thus the predictions of MAP are more likely to be overcondent.

6.4.4 Out-of-distribution detection metrics
We measure some metrics to evaluate the models ability of distinguishing in- and
out-of-distribution images. The synthesis results are shown in Table 6.2.
An ideal classier should have a low probability of false alarm, corresponding to a
low False Positive Rate (FPR), while maintaining a high sensitivity, corresponding
to a high True Positive Rate (TPR). FPR at 95% TPR is a suitable metric to
measure the reality of this desire.
Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve plots the TPR against the FPR at all
possible decision thresholds. The larger the Area Under the ROC curve (AUROC),
the better the classiers ability to separate the negative and positive samples. More
intuitively, AUROC indicates the chance that the classier produces a higher score
on a random positive sample than a random negative one.
Besides the ROC curve, which represents the trade-off between the sensitivity and
the probability of false alarm, Precision-Recall (PR) curves are often plotted to
